Indigenous Peoples‚Äô Day is celebrated on the second Monday of October to honor the cultures and histories of the Native American people. With this in mind, let‚Äôs take a moment to celebrate Buffy Sainte-Marie! Buffy Sainte-Marie is a Canadian-American Cree singer-songwriter, musician, composer, visual artist, educator, pacifist and social activist. Throughout her career in all of these areas, her work has focused on issues of indigenous peoples of the Americas. Her singing and writing repertoire also includes subjects of love, war, religion, and mysticism. In 1997, Buffy founded the Cradleboard Teaching Project, an educational curriculum devoted to better understanding Native Americans. She has won recognition and many awards and honors for both her music and her work in education and social activism. Her 19th album, ‚ÄúMedicine Songs‚Äù (2017), features a mix of new material, such as ‚ÄúYou Got to Run (Spirit of the Wind),‚Äù a collaboration with Tanya Tagaq, and re-recorded older songs, including ‚ÄúStarwalker,‚Äù ‚ÄúLittle Wheel Spin and Spin‚Äù and ‚ÄúBury My Heart at Wounded Knee.‚Äù The album drew positive reviews and went on to win the 2018 Juno Award for Indigenous Music Album of the Year. Of the album, ‚ÄúNOW‚Äù magazine‚Äôs Michael Rancic wrote: ‚ÄúAnother artist might show signs of disappointment or uncertainty when faced with the notion that not much has changed in half a century, but on ‚ÄúMedicine Songs‚Äù, in the face of the unchanging nature of the oppression she‚Äôs expressed through her music, Buffy Sainte-Marie has chosen to be just as determined, unflinching and constant in her own art.‚Äù In the video below, Buffy Sainte-Marie and Tanya Tagaq perform "You Got to Run (Spirit of the Wind)". The song was written by Sainte-Marie and inspired by champion dogsled racer George Attla, who competed in the first-ever Iditarod dog sled race in 1973 and was the subject of the 1979 film, ‚ÄúSpirit of the Wind‚Äù. The film shows the life of George Attla as a young Athabaskan trapper living in the bush in Alaska and then in a TB sanitarium in town. Today, President Abdel Fattah El-Sisi received a phone call from Turkish President Recep Tayyip Erdoƒüan. Spokesman for the Presidency Counselor Ahmed Fahmy said the call touched on consultations on efforts to contain the escalation between the Palestinian and Israeli sides, in light of the successive developments at this level that portend dire consequences for the security and stability of the region. The two presidents agreed on the importance of urging all parties to immediately stop the confrontations and violence, and to avoid exposing civilians to further risks and loss of life, taking into account the need to protect civilians and secure humanitarian conditions suitable for their livelihood. The two presidents also stressed that permanently ending the Palestinian-Israeli conflict comes through providing hope and political prospect, and implementing the two-state solution based on the approved terms of reference and the relevant resolutions of international legitimacy.

The Ancient War Principles of the Dinka and Nilotics The Dinka, Nuer, and other Nilotic tribes, proud of their heritage, used to follow unwritten codes during traditional conflicts. Historically, these disputes were over territories, water sources, resources, and other factors that led to these confrontations. The essence of these battles wasn't merely about victory or demonstrating one's strength and bravery to the adversary. The operation had a restricted scope because no community wanted the other to be cleansed. Not all wars were intentional. None of the communities initiated an attack because they wanted to compare it to our present world. Whether the conflict involved individuals or entire communities, adherence to these codes was paramount. A notable practice among the Dinka was their aversion to surprise attacks, especially when combat was primarily with sticks or spears. If one were to ambush an adversary, the norm was to gently tap them on the shoulder, giving them a moment to recognise their attacker. This practice stemmed from the Ji…õÃà≈ã's deep-rooted belief that blindsiding an opponent was dishonourable. They held that such actions displeased the divine, potentially invoking a curse upon the perpetrator for harming an unsuspecting soul. Furthermore, there were strict prohibitions against harming the elderly, women, children, the frail, or even prisoners of war. While men might fall in battle, children were spared, ensuring the continuity of life and culture even amidst conflict. Once hostilities ceased, efforts were made to mend ties, with reparations and reconciliation processes initiated to foster harmony and coexistence. Sadly, these communities' rich traditions, values, and ethics face challenges today. I passionately hope the upcoming generations remember and cherish the profound values and norms that once defined our societies. #AjakDengChiengkou

On this day in 1956, America welcomed my dad (pictured center) and his family as Palestinian Christian refugees. It was the greatest blessing of his life. Born Attallah Amash in 1940, my dad had an extremely difficult childhood. He was a victim of war, expelled from his home at just eight years old in 1948, moving from place to place to find shelter and living off scraps. He never had new clothes except what was provided to him through charity. In the few years (on and off) that he was able to attend school, the other children didn‚Äôt want to associate with him. He couldn‚Äôt even play soccer with them because he didn‚Äôt have shoes. His father made him sell coffee and tea as a young boy just to make a few cents that his dad would take. The first time my dad had a decent meal was when a family member died (an uncle, who lived and died in a dog house) and neighbors delivered food in his memory. Even before the conflict, my dad‚Äôs family lived in abject poverty. His grandma, grandpa, aunt, and uncle died of starvation under Ottoman rule. They lived in horrendous conditions among rats. They were abused, uneducated, prone to superstitions, and struggled with mental illness. The Amash family‚Äôs misfortune turned into triumph when Rev. & Mrs. Ralph Wagoner (pictured right), of the Muskegon Church of the Brethren, made the sacrifice to sponsor them to come to the United States. The incredible generosity of the Wagoners gave new life to the Amashes. I‚Äôm forever grateful to the Wagoners for making my life in America possible. I‚Äôm forever grateful to America for opening its arms to poor refugees like my dad‚Äôs family. This story is why I so dearly love our Constitution, which defends life, liberty, and property. It‚Äôs why I wanted to serve in Congress: to support, with my voice and votes, the great principles that define America. I was honored that my community here in Michigan gave me that opportunity.

The most fool-proof way to know when a person is cheating is a shift in their baseline temperament. That is, a deviation from their normal behaviour in situations. Every couple knows their expected range of expression. How calm they are in normal circumstances, how they behave when angry or anxious, how they interact when there's tension between them. There is a rhythm to their energy when it's the two of them. But the moment a third person is plugged into the matrix, there will be a shift. The cheating person will experience guilt, and they will need to offset it. If they think of their partner as loving and committed, they will feel immense guilt for cheating on a person who is so good and loyal. So, to reduce this guilt, they must exaggerate the partner's weaker qualities to get some justification for cheating. They will overreact to things and prolong conflict more than usual. They will one disagreement to explain a lot of change in their own behaviour. The truth is that they're y're trying to convince themselves, not you. Alternatively, they will become inexplicably nice in an attempt to 'make it up for you.' They will seem happier and more excited without any reason. Nobody can perfectly balance these two experiences. Your solution is to stop focusing on the theatrics in the house. When you see strange behaviour, always look behind the person. You can't confront too soon because they'll just gaslight you and cover their tracks better. You have to contain yourself and fish for solid evidence, usually something around their communications or unexplained leave of absence. But remember you must be prepared to deal with a potential end of this relationship. If you don't know what you can do in case you confirm your fears, you will avoid digging. The problem will get worse and swallow your health and well-being. The first rule for a healthy relationship is to always marry life before you marry anyone so that your life will never depend on the one you marry. That is, learb to live on your own first so that those who get to live with you don't think they are your life. People cheat with impunity when they think you can't go anywhere. The moment they know you'll just shut them out at once, they will think twice before playing you. In essence, you maintain a healthy marriage by not needing it as a matter of life and death. Sin will be rampant everywhere, and the love of many will grow cold. But the one who endures to the end will be saved.‚Äù (Matthew 24:6-13) The first thing I notice about this passage is the command of ‚Äúdon‚Äôt panic.‚Äù Our job as Christians is to not be caught up with the rest of the world with the spirit of fear. ‚ÄúGod has not given us a spirit of fear and timidity, but of power, love, and self-discipline.‚Äù (2 Tim. 1:7) The second thing I notice about this passage is Jesus telling us when we hear of ‚Äúwars and rumors of wars‚Äù that ‚Äúthe end won‚Äôt follow immediately.‚Äù We might be living in the end times, but this is not the end of the end according to Jesus. The third thing I notice here is Jesus‚Äô stern warning against false prophets. It‚Äôs easy when there is fear and turmoil to cling to words that make us feel good, but they may not necessarily be what the Bible says. Beware of false teachers, be grounded in the word of God. This is no time to follow popular opinions. This is a time to stand on God‚Äôs word. So what's our assignment as Christians? Jesus says in Luke 19:13, "Occupy until I come." The end times are not a time to sit on your rapture rug and wait until Jesus comes back. The end times are for a glorious church to rise and to rule and reign with Christ as "kings and priests unto our God." (Rev. 1:6) Now is the time to take our royal authority over the darkness, to push back the darkness, to contend for souls, to go to war with our prayers and spiritual weapons. Jesus is not coming back for a weak bride. Jesus is coming back for a warrior bride. Now is the time to take authority over the darkness and to push back the gates of hell with our prayers. So when you hear of wars and rumors of wars, don't panic. Jesus said this is not the end of the end. Occupy until Christ comes. Push back the gates of hell with your prayers and weapons of warfare. Stand on the word and sound doctrine. And remember your prayers are more powerful than you realize. They can pull down the demonic strongholds in the earth, which in turn changes the physical realm. When we go after the kingdom of hell in prayer, we will begin to see the victory in the physical realm as well. Pray for Israel. Pray for the nations of the world. Pray bold prayers and take authority over the dark powers and demons. Christ gave you that authority. The church is the hope of the world. "Upon this rock I will build my church, and all the powers of hell will not conquer it." (Matt. 16:18)

My heart goes out to all the victims and their families of the current escalation of this ongoing conflict between Israel and Hamas. Social media is not a place for nuanced discussions or complicated issues, so I usually try to keep my thoughts to when I can actually have real meaningful conversation with people face to face. However, yesterday‚Äôs attack by the Hamas militants is something we haven‚Äôt seen yet. Perhaps because Hamas was never as successful as this, or perhaps just because violence and cruelty have a way of escalating where civility is allowed to erode. Even in the surreal status quo of bloodshed and despair that we have gotten used to over the many years of conflict, there seemed to be some general rules, which have been finally crushed yesterday morning. This was not just an indiscriminate rampage of violence. This was a planned and systematic slaughter, targeting helpless civilians‚Ä¶ babies, children and elderly included, followed by the cheering and the abuse of the paraded bodies in Gaza‚Äôs streets. The videos circulating in social medias are something that should send shivering chills in any beating human heart. They certainly have kept me up in a strange, numbing tempest of horror tonight. And while, of course there is a context for everything, and I am on the side that truly believes that the Palestinian people deserve to have their own governance and freedom, no context or ideal in the world can justify these actions. Moreover, I know as well as anyone, that these horrific acts of bloodlust and brutality only lead to a circle of retaliation and violence and loss. It saddens me, and despairs me. I wish I could say that distance makes it easier. But my heart truly shatters at the level of cruelty and inhumanity of the past two days. To my family, and my friends, to those who have lost, to those who are trapped in this gruesome cycle, I send my condolences, I send my love and strength and above all, I send my heartbroken prayers for more peaceful times to come.

10ID awards medal to soldier who apprehends a snatcher in Tagum City MAWAB, Davao De Oro - Private First Class Junnel M Perdido, a soldier of the 10th Installation and Management Battalion (10IMB), was awarded the Bronze Cross Medal during the Monday Flag Raising Ceremony held at Camp General Manuel T. Yan Senior in Mawab, Davao De Oro on October 9, 2023. PFC Perdido fearlessly pursued a snatcher who stole the wallet of Mrs. Lorife Ulep, containing P30,000.00 as payment for her daughter's hospital bill at Aquino Hospital, Tagum City, on September 28. PFC Perdido's heroic act did not involve actual conflict but rather a life-threatening risk as he chased and apprehended the snatcher hiding in a nearby village despite the potential danger. Brigadier General Allan D Hambala, Acting Commander of the 10th Infantry (Agila) Division, personally pinned the medal on PFC Perdido and subsequently commended his heroism and dedication to duty. In an interview, Mr. Efren Ulep, the victim's husband, expressed his gratitude for PFC Perdido's heroism. "Mabuti sir at may tumulong. Hindi na man siya duty diba, pero si sir (referring to PFC Perdido) ginamit niya ang sinumpaan niya," Mr. Ulep said in vernacular. PFC Perdido is a member of the Morale and Welfare Recovery Center of the 10IMB under the Operational Control of the 10ID. He was at the hospital with his pregnant wife and daughter for a medical check-up while on leave. #StrongerArmyStrongerCountry #AgilaNewsNetwork #AgilaTroopers

Please read the following update from Daniel Pierce about some of the ways we have been able to help in Israel right now: Earlier today, Max Voloshin went out to purchase groceries for displaced families from southern communities in Israel. (Max is one of our employees and our building manager in Jerusalem.) We also donated groceries to an organization that distributes food to the IDF soldiers who are currently amassed on Israel‚Äôs borders in preparation for the conflict over the coming days and weeks. We have opened up our home, and the Glory of Zion Jerusalem Ministry Center to accommodate families from the south who need to take shelter outside of the Gaza area. We are so blessed to have the Ministry Center and home in Jerusalem to serve the community in this way. When Max arrived to stock our home with groceries, the alarm sirens went off in Jerusalem. Max and his girlfriend took shelter in our safe room and counted ten explosions over the city. This was the second rocket attack on Jerusalem today. Tel Aviv also had rockets this morning. Max also shared with us that the grocery stores are very crowded and food is going fast. The city is currently shut down other than the grocery stores and people have been instructed to shelter in place. Thank you for continuing to pray for Israel and support in every way we are called to through Glory of Zion International.

One of the many non-motorised items of German-wheeled transport in WWII was the Infantry Trailer IF-8. We currently have two restored examples and a third one waiting to be restored in the future. The lack of motorised transport plagued the German forces during the conflict, which is why the "Infanteriekarren IF-8" was produced in vast numbers, approximately 100,000. These infantry trailers had 12 different arrangements, from transporting ammunition, mortars, and MG 34 to field telephones and medical equipment. Horses, mules, bicycles, motorcycle sidecars, and these infantry trailers were in many cases the only modes of transport that many German infantry units ever had to carry equipment and provide any form of mobility. Learn more about these trailers and how important they are by visiting our website.

Living in multicultural Australia means I‚Äôm exposed directly to the heartbreaking stories of ethnic conflict from all corners of the world. Without having the livid experience of being those people and sharing that history, there is only so much I can understand about their deep rooted personal and historical desire to fight for or defend what they see as their homeland. As an individual I‚Äôm sympathetic to my friends from around the world and think how blessed we are to be in a country that shows our differences have very little to do with how we can all live together in peace. Living in Australia also means that we are a part of civilised society that condemn acts of savagery and barbarism. We have our own moral and ethical aspirations to be people who despite the conflict, value human life, especially the protection of innocent civilian life at all times. Even when our own nation fails to meet these standards we condemn it and seek to hold our own accountable. It is shameful that there are those in my country, including political parties, movements and their leaders who are unable to rise to this standard today. If you are standing in solidarity with the savagery of directly slaughtering civilians, the parading of mutilated corpses, the hostage taking and rape of women and children as acceptable forms of resistance and defence, please think long and hard about what you are endorsing. It is worrying that so many here in Australia that are not linked to this conflict by ethnicity or history are unable to be rational and think clearly during a time like this. If we also rise to the depths of an eye for an eye bloodlust that excuses acts of savagery against innocents, there is not a hope in the world for the people directly impacted by those conflicts.

This significant milestone fills our hearts with pride and gratitude, marking a journey of resilience, unity, and the unwavering spirit of our people. This year's Fiji Day theme, "Rebuilding Fiji Together," reflects not only our aspirations but also the indomitable spirit that has guided us through the years. It underscores our commitment to stand shoulder to shoulder, forging a brighter future for all Fijians. Today, I wish to expand upon this theme, intertwining it with a vision that transcends our national borders - the "Pacific Zone of Peace." Recently, I had the privilege of representing our beloved Fiji at the United Nations General Assembly in New York. There, on the global stage, we introduced the concept of the "Pacific Zone of Peace" as our Blue Pacific's invaluable contribution to global order. This vision embodies the very essence of our commitment to peace, mutual respect, and unity in our region. The "Pacific Zone of Peace" is rooted in the fundamental values of mutual respect for each other's sovereignty, territorial integrity, and political independence. It calls for the nurturing and enhancement of international cooperation, inviting nations to collaborate on areas of common interest. In an ever-changing world, it reminds us of the power of unity and our shared responsibility to create a better future. We, in the Pacific, face unique challenges. The threats of climate change loom large, casting a shadow over our islands and communities. Rising sea levels, frequent cyclones, and the displacement of our people are daily reminders of the urgency to address this crisis. It is in these trying times that the "Pacific Zone of Peace" becomes not just an aspiration but a lifeline - a call for global solidarity in the face of environmental challenges that threaten our very existence. Today, as we celebrate our independence, we are reminded that peace is not only the absence of conflict but also the presence of cooperation and understanding among our people. In our multicultural society, peace serves as the cornerstone that nurtures unity and drives progress. It empowers us to harness the collective strength of our diverse backgrounds, cultures, and traditions. In our rapidly developing nation, peace is the catalyst for innovation, investment, and economic growth. It attracts partners and investors who recognise the stability and potential of a peaceful Fiji. It equips us to confront the challenges of climate change and global disruptions with resilience and determination. Our commitment to the "Pacific Zone of Peace" reinforces our dedication to fostering regional and global collaboration. It sends a resounding message that Fiji is a staunch advocate for peace, both at home and on the international stage. As we rejoice in the spirit of independence, let us rekindle our commitment to safeguarding and enhancing the peace that underpins our progress. Together, as one united people, we will continue to build a Fiji that thrives economically and stands as a shining example of unity in diversity. ùêáùêöùê©ùê©ùê≤ ùêÖùê¢ùê£ùê¢ ùêÉùêöùê≤ ùê≠ùê® ùêöùê•ùê•! the dedicated president of the Shaar Negev Regional Council, who was tragically killed while defending his residents from Hamas terrorists. Just a few weeks ago, I had the privilege of walking alongside Ofir. He spoke with passion about the region he loved so profoundly. He had grand dreams for Shaar Negev ‚Äî from elevating student life at Sapir College to catalyzing growth in local businesses, hi-tech ventures, and agriculture. More than just infrastructure, Ofir imagined a community thriving beyond the shadows of conflict. He was determined not to let the terrorists from Gaza dictate his residents' quality of life. Furthermore, he hoped to build bridges with the people of Gaza. He recognized many there who desired progress. He was clear in his stance: not to cooperate with Hamas, a terror organization, but to establish direct connections with the Gaza residents he saw as victims of Hamas. While we didn't always agree on every nuance, I deeply respected his vision and commitment. He was a true patriot, both for his community and the nation. After departing from the corporate realm, Ofir poured his heart and soul into these dreams. The heartbreak is palpable, knowing he won't witness these dreams realized. He had set his sights on retirement in 5 years, aiming to immerse himself in educating young Jews globally, fostering their connection to Israel. Although he won't be able to fulfill this dream himself, I am resolute in my commitment to ensuring his story and ideals resonate worldwide, perpetuating his legacy. Ofir, your impact was profound. You'll be profoundly missed by all fortunate enough to have known you. You were a hero throughout your life, and in your final moments, you bravely protected your people.

Watching in horror the brutal massacre, kidnappings, murder and torturing of innocent civilians in Israel by Hamas, a terrorist organisation determined to kill Jews and abolish the state of Israel. I‚Äôve been amazed by how little empathy or even acknowledgment people have shown to what‚Äôs been going on. Somehow condemning terror that‚Äôs directed at children, women and old ladies is ok if the victims are Israeli, or is it Jews? I forget. And yea, you can totally be critical of Israel‚Äôs government (past and current), their policies and actions over the years, and support the Palestinian people‚Äôs right to freedom and land (I do too) without being antisemitic, but if you say nothing against this horror and somehow find ways to justify it, then chances are that you ARE antisemitic whether you realise it or not. Jews around the world are being targeted as we speak. People who have no contact with Israel, some have never even visited and are unable to impact its politics, today walk in fear. Why is that?! The inability to separate between Jews and the Israeli government IS antisemitism and is as damaging as the inability to separate between the Palestinian people and Hamas. It‚Äôs a result of ignorance and I urge anyone who feels ‚Äúconfused‚Äù (I‚Äôve heard that word several times over the past few days) to educate themselves. I‚Äôve written an article about the Middle East conflict for those who want to learn more and I‚Äôve linked in my bio, but beyond the analytical understanding of the situation, I urge you to not forget your humanity. Hamas has kidnapped toddlers. TODDLERS. Are they to blame for Israel government‚Äôs injustices? Are we saying that it‚Äôs ok to rape and kill in some situations? Condemning Hamas does not mean ignoring the Palestinians‚Äô suffering. Over the years they have lost many lives including innocent children and women and every single one of them was a tragic loss. If we are able to say that about them then we should be able to say the same about Israeli children. Regardless of our politics. Praying for peace & freedom for everyone ‚ù§Ô∏èüôèüèª #love

I often talk about people-pleasing isn‚Äôt really about pleasing people; it‚Äôs how we learned to stay physically, emotionally, or socially safe. But this coping mechanism we learned in the past wreaks havoc on our relationships in the present. Ultimately, people-pleasing‚Äôs inevitable consequences‚Äîyears‚Äô worth of resentment, avoidance, conflict aversion, and unspoken grievances‚Äîinhibit us from truly connecting with the very people we care about. They also prevent others from knowing who we really are. True intimacy requires that we release our stronghold on this outdated coping mechanism. It requires that we share the depths of our own passions and dreams. It demands that we are honest about what we feel and need, even when it‚Äôs hard. Ultimately, accepting the invitation to intimacy means bringing more self to our relationships after years of bringing less. ‚ÄúFor the first time in decades, Israel called the conflict with Palestinians a state of war. But for Palestinians, being at war is an enduring reality that has shaped their daily lives for the past seven decades. Since the Palestinian Nakba in 1948, which resulted in the forcible displacement of 750,000 Palestinians from their towns and villages, successive Israeli governments have committed hundreds of human rights violations, including ethnic cleansing, apartheid, and mass killings, all of which amount to war crimes according to international law. While Palestinians have long said that Israel‚Äôs practices are part of a war waged against their very existence, Israel has managed to get away with its violations, enjoying complete impunity that has lasted for more than 75 years. At 6.30am on Saturday, residents in Gaza were abruptly awakened by the sound of explosions reverberating through the blockaded Strip. By this time, it was not another Israeli military assault; rather, it was barrages of Palestinian homemade rockets launched towards several towns and cities in Israel. While the attack is described as ‚Äòsurprising‚Äô by many, an escalation of events was undoubtedly expected, given Israel‚Äôs tightening of restrictions and the rise in assaults across the occupied Palestinian territories during the past few months. This rise in Israeli military and settler brutality signifies an unprecedented level of violence across all the Palestinian territories, fueled and encouraged by a troubling sense of impunity and a lack of accountability for those responsible. Residents of Gaza have been talking of a fresh escalation since the early months of 2023: those discussions became ever more prominent both during and following each Israeli surge in violence in the occupied territories. And for them, the attack by Palestinian armed factions against Israel this weekend was not so much a surprise in concept as in scale and nature, both of which were unprecedented in the history of the Israeli-Palestinian conflict.‚Äù ‚úç: Maha Hussaini * Views expressed in this column belong to the author and do not necessarily reflect the editorial policy of MEE

THE FRENCH GOVERNMENT THANKS PRESIDENT KIIR FOR HIS OPEN DOOR POLICY FOR REFUGEES JUBA- 9 October 2023---- President Kiir on Monday met with the visiting French legislators, to discuss the humanitarian crisis brought about by the Sudanese conflict. The Chairperson of "French Parliamentary Caucus on South Sudan" Christophe Marion said they are in Juba to have a better understanding of the war in Sudan and its impacts on South Sudan and the entire region. Marion said with the prevailing situation, "we are convinced that South Sudan could be an element of stability and can contribute to the stability of the sub-region". The French legislator said his government would establish partnership with South Sudan in areas of culture, agriculture, finance and the economy. Foreign Minister Dr. James Pitia Morgan said the French legislators thank President Kiir for opening the door for the Sudanese refugees to come to South Sudan without any difficulty. Minister Morgan noted that President Kiir has assured the delegation of his administration's commitment to providing a conducive environment for the conduct of the election in 2024. Morgan said South Sudan and France enjoy cordial relations, and that they are working together to reinforce the long standing relationship between Juba and Paris.

I think a large part of my discontent is the lack of thought in reactions and responses to Trek. It used to be something you could nerd out about because there was story and canon most took the time to study and discuss. Now a days it's labeled and dismissed casually. Safe example: Janeway stated in the premiere of the series that they were stranded with no way to resupply that they had a finite amount of weapons and materials. In the first season it was established that Voyager required regular maintenance and upkeep to keep going. While under warp they had to cut back on energy intensive activities, if they wanted to use the replicator w/o limits they had to be out of warp. Any major repairs they had to park the ship on a planetary body. Within those constraints they could resupply their weapons, build shuttlecraft, and do major repairs ,.... to a point. After the third or so time that someone who wasn't paying attention sneered about Voyager having more photon torpedoes, or having an unlimited amount of shuttlecraft, it just kills the buzz on enjoying a series with others. Almost ALL of Trek has underlying reasons for why things are the way they are. Most "plotholes" or "bad writing" is usually just not understanding what was being depicted. I say "most" because things like Tuvix happened. Over two hundred years on data about transporters, four clear examples on how to resolve bringing back Tuvok and Neelix without killing Tuvix, and the writers when for drama and conflict. I miss being able to talk w/o someone trolling the subject.

In times of darkness and despair, it is crucial that we all come together to advocate a lasting and sustainable peace.

Appeal to Armenian diaspora organizations from the International Foundation of World Azerbaijanis (IFWA): After more than thirty years of conflict, the military confrontation between Azerbaijan and Armenia has come to an end. The leaders of Azerbaijan and Armenia are currently continuing their efforts to achieve a peace agreement between the two countries. Both leaders have repeatedly declared that a peace agreement can only be signed under condition of mutual recognition of territorial integrity and sovereignty. As a consequence, some major and important tasks stand before intellectuals, public organizations and diaspora organizations of the two countries; these include supporting the leaders‚Äô peace efforts, building bridges of trust and confidence between the two neighbouring countries and paving the way of their peaceful coexistence. Following the local anti-terrorist measures conducted by Azerbaijan which aimed to restore constitutional structure within its borders, peaceful Armenian residents, voluntarily or under the influence of other forces, left their homes and moved to Armenia and third countries. The President of Azerbaijan, Mr. Ilham Aliyev has repeatedly stated that the ethnic Armenians living in the Karabakh region are citizens of Azerbaijan and their rights and security will be ensured according to the Constitution of Azerbaijan. In the face of this reality, there is a serious need for joint efforts of progressive forces in both countries to advance cause of peace and overcome hostility between the two nations. It is no secret that, as in past years, there are international powers who still resist stability in the region and normalization of relations between the two neighbouring nations. Some groups, being used by international powers as pawns, are also striving to prevent the establishment of normal relations between the Azerbaijani and Armenian people. The IFWA, which includes numerous Azerbaijani diaspora organizations, believes that the organizations of both diasporas should refrain from any actions that incite enmity between the two nations. Such actions are nothing but obstacles to processes towards peace and peaceful coexistence that are being developed in the region. Diaspora organizations operating abroad should not incite discord or enmity in the region, but should promote peace and peaceful coexistence. Rushing to the streets located hundreds of kilometres away from the South Caucasus region, inciting confrontation and organizing raids on diplomatic missions does not contribute to region‚Äôs prosperity in any way. Karabakh, a cradle of culture, has always been rich in its ethnic diversity. To rebuild its stable ethnic structure and to achieve lasting peace in the region, both Armenian and Azerbaijani diaspora organizations should spare no effort in supporting normalization of relations and reintegration. The people of two states that have a common border spreading over hundreds of kilometres, have no choice but to live in peace, recognize and respect each other's territorial integrity. The large-scale development and construction works currently ongoing in Karabakh aim to improve social welfare of all people living in the region, regardless of their ethnicity. The state of Azerbaijan carries out acontinuous work to ensure sustainable reintegration of Armenian citizens residing in the Karabakh region into our society. The working group created for this purpose has been assigned relevant tasks aimed to resolve social, humanitarian, economic and infrastructure issues in the Karabakh region. This work includes registration of Armenian residents living in the Karabakh region, understanding their needs and proposing measures for solving problems they may face. IFWA hopes that responsible organizations of Armenian diaspora will renounce regressive efforts and actions against Azerbaijan and support reintegration of Armenians living in Karabakh into Azerbaijani society. IFWA believes that cooperation between the two diaspora organizations is vital for promotion of peace and reintegration, and expresses readiness to support joint efforts in this direction. God we pray for peace in Israel üôèüèº üáÆüá± What does the Bible say about the conflict in Israel? Jesus said in Matthew 24, ‚ÄúYou will hear of wars and threats of wars, but don‚Äôt panic. Yes, these things must take place, but the end won‚Äôt follow immediately. Nation will go to war against nation, and kingdom against kingdom. There will be famines and earthquakes in many parts of the world. But all this is only the first of the birth pains, with more to come. Then you will be arrested, persecuted, and killed. You will be hated all over the world because you are my followers. And many will turn away from me and betray and hate each other. And many false prophets will appear and will deceive many people. Sin will be rampant everywhere, and the love of many will grow cold. But the one who endures to the end will be saved.‚Äù (Matthew 24:6-13) The first thing I notice about this passage is the command of ‚Äúdon‚Äôt panic.‚Äù Our job as Christians is to not be caught up with the rest of the world with the spirit of fear. ‚ÄúGod has not given us a spirit of fear and timidity, but of power, love, and self-discipline.‚Äù (2 Tim. 1:7) The second thing I notice about this passage is Jesus telling us when we hear of ‚Äúwars and rumors of wars‚Äù that ‚Äúthe end won‚Äôt follow immediately.‚Äù We might be living in the end times, but this is not the end of the end according to Jesus. The third thing I notice here is Jesus‚Äô stern warning against false prophets. It‚Äôs easy when there is fear and turmoil to cling to words that make us feel good, but they may not necessarily be what the Bible says. Beware of false teachers, be grounded in the word of God. This is no time to follow popular opinions. This is a time to stand on God‚Äôs word. So what's our assignment as Christians? Jesus says in Luke 19:13, "Occupy until I come." The end times are not a time to sit on your rapture rug and wait until Jesus comes back. The end times are for a glorious church to rise and to rule and reign with Christ as "kings and priests unto our God." (Rev. 1:6) Now is the time to take our royal authority over the darkness, to push back the darkness, to contend for souls, to go to war with our prayers and spiritual weapons. Jesus is not coming back for a weak bride. Jesus is coming back for a warrior bride. Now is the time to take authority over the darkness and to push back the gates of hell with our prayers. I have a very close relationship with ◊î◊õ◊ï◊®◊°◊ê ◊î◊ï◊¶◊ê◊î ◊ú◊ê◊ï◊®, my publishing house in Israel, including a wonderful friendship with publisher Hilit Hamou-Meir. Not so long ago, she sent me a beautiful basket of handmade wares (and chocolates!) from Galilee, which I treasure; it sits just beside my desk. And when I was diagnosed with breast cancer last year, she immediately helped me to connect with Israeli breast cancer organization One in Nine so that I could reach Israeli readers with my story and encourage them to stay up to date with their mammograms. I have a tremendous respect for her, and for the many readers there in Israel who have reached out to me over the years. Just as many of us have, I've felt very helpless these last two days watching the terrible events in Israel unfold from afar. I asked Hilit over the weekend if she could suggest an organization that concerned Americans might be able to donate to, to help provide humanitarian aid to Israelis impacted by the terrorist attacks, and she suggested this campaign: https://www.americaisraeldemocracy.org/southunderattack It looks like the organization, a U.S.-based 501(c)(3) nonprofit, was founded to "educate, strengthen, and preserve the democratic foundations of the State of Israel," but this particular campaign promises to "support medical, psycho-social, physical assistance and aid for families with members kidnapped to Gaza." I don't know enough about the organization to personally endorse it, but I did a bit of research and made a donation there myself this morning. Another organization doing good work in the region: Save the Children, which has been working with children impacted by the ongoing conflict since 1953, with a permanent presence in Gaza since 1973. They help both Palestinian and Israeli children--I think we can all agree that no child, on either side of the border, should have to live through what's happening right now: https://www.savethechildren.org/us/where-we-work/west-bank-gaza#statement:=:https://www.savethechildren.org/us/where-we-work/west-bank-gaza I made a donation to Save the Children, too. KABATAAN PARTYLIST ON THE ISRAEL-PALESTINE CONFLICT Tumitindig ang Kabataan Partylist para sa tunay na kalayaan at kapayapaan sa mga lupaing okupado ng Israel. Ninanais natin ang kaligtasan ng mga mamamayang apektado ng umiigting na labanan sa pagitan ng mga Palestino at ng pamahalaan ng Israel. Batay sa datos ng United Nations (UN), hindi kamakailan lamang nagsimula ang labanan. Sa huling labinlimang (15) taon, nasa 6,400 mamamayang Palestino ang namatay at mahigit 120,000 ng sugatan, habang nasa 300 naman ang nasawi at mahigit 6,000 ang sugatan sa panig ng Israel. Bunga ito ng pitumpu't limang (75) taong okupasyon ng gobyerno ng Israel sa mga teritoryo ng Palestine, kabilang ang Gaza at West Bank, na nagpalayas sa daan-daang libong Palestino mula sa kanilang mga komunidad at nilalagay ang mamamayang Israeli sa mabuway na kalagayan ng pamumuhay. Labag sa pandaigdigang batas at maituturing na krimen sa digmaan o 'war crime' ang deka-dekadang okupasyon, at maging ang mga kinatawan ng UN ay naglabas ng mga pahayag laban dito. Gayumpaman, nagiging posible pa rin ang okupasyon dahil sa pagsuporta ng gobyerno ng Estados Unidos sa gobyerno ng Israel, na siyang pinakamalaking tumatanggap ng dayuhang tulong pinansyal mula sa Estados Unidos. Taliwas sa tindig ng UN, sinusuportahan ng Estados Unidos ang okupasyon at hinaharangan o pinalalabnaw ang mga resolusyon ng UN na kumukondena sa mga abuso at paglabag sa karapatan ng mga mamamayang naninirahan sa mga okupadong lugar. Makakamit lamang ang tunay na kapayapaan at kalayaan para sa mga Palestino at Israeli kapag napawi na ang ugat ng labanan. Kailangang tapusin na ang okupasyon ng Gaza at West Bank, at dapat itigil ng ibang mga bansa ang pagsuporta sa mga pwersang nagtutulak ng okupasyon. Sa kagyat, dapat maprotektahan ang buhay ng lahat ng mga sibilyan habang nangyayari ang labanan. Krimen sa digmaan ang pagtarget sa mga paaralan, moske at bahay ng mga sibilyan sa Gaza; krimen din ang planong blockade sa Gaza na maghaharang sa akses ng mahigit 2 milyong sibilyan sa kuryente, pagkain, tubig at iba pang batayang pangangailangan. Suportado ng Kabataan Partylist ang mga hakbang para mabilis na protektahan ang mga migranteng Pilipino na nasa mga apektadong lugar at ilikas ang ating mga OFW papunta sa mas ligtas na matutuluyan. Dapat mapakawalan sa lalong madaling panahon ang sinumang Pilipinong magiging bihag ng mga armadong pwersang bahagi ng labanan. ### PRESS STATEMENT October 9, 2023

text: #mondaymotivation Love in the midst of life There‚Äôs only places the right two can go. With the wrong hand in yours There really is no telling where you will be led. Wrong words, wrong places, wrong feelings, wrong stories, fake smiles , wrong just wrong. The right person will make you care if the stars are out , or if the breeze is just enough to send you the scent of their hair. They know your heart, and your flaws, and it somehow creates the right combination to fit the complex puzzle of theirs. Forgiveness and compromise comes natural. You know their love wouldn‚Äôt allow for intentional pain or conflict. They would gladly bleed for you, in any situation that may apply. When sudden stops happen on trips, your right hand instinctively goes out in an attempt to be the external force that could overcome and protect them from inertia. Thought of self safety and health at times fall by the wayside. Because without them and their well-being you would feel like the lone dove. No longer wanting wind giving lift to your wings in what seems to be every pointless flight. It‚Äôs so easy to let time slip by without putting gratitude towards the importance of what could leave you any second without warning. Love in life is no different from a house fire, or a tragic accident. Except the pain never gets better. It‚Äôs loss not replaced with the right policy. It finds a place to reside and lingers like the ghosts of war. You forget there are stars. The moon is just another reminder that it too is alone. Be grateful. The US will likely 'go to war' in Israel with air and naval power if Syria or Iran become actively involved, retired 4-star general says Amid heightened tensions in the Middle East, Ret. Gen. Barry McCaffrey expressed concerns that the U.S. may be forced into military intervention in Israel if neighboring nations become more involved in the ongoing conflict. McCaffrey, during his appearance on MSNBC's "Weekends with Alex Witt," emphasized that the U.S. would consider direct intervention with air and naval strikes, especially if Israel's existence is at stake due to escalating actions from countries like Syria and Iran. Commenting on the potential involvement of regional powers, he said, "The other shoe we're waiting to see if it drops is, will Hezbollah intervene out of Lebanon with their 100,000 some odd rockets? Will the West Bank ignite? And what will the Syrians and the Egyptians do?" This came after Hamas militants launched a series of attacks against Israel, resulting in significant casualties on both sides. Israel, in retaliation, has declared war. The U.S., in response to the situation, announced the deployment of an aircraft carrier strike group to patrol the Eastern Mediterranean, aiming to deter a full-blown war involving Israel and its neighboring countries. McCaffrey, drawing from his experience from the Gulf War and his tenure leading the U.S. Southern Command, believes the U.S. show of force isn't purely symbolic. He stated, "They're there for more than a show of force or a potential noncombatant evacuation." However, he also clarified that while air and naval power might be deployed, it's improbable that U.S. ground troops would enter Israel, given the nation's own potent ground forces. When questioned about possible involvement from other allies, McCaffrey felt it was premature to speculate but highlighted the Biden administration's goal of deterrence. "They want to make sure that the Syrian military and Hezbollah don't enter this fray," he noted. Hezbollah, meanwhile, announced its shelling of the Golan Heights, an area annexed by Israel from Syria in 1981, expressing solidarity with "Palestinian resistance." Reports from The Wall Street Journal indicate a collaboration between Iranian officials and Hamas in preparation for the recent incursions into Israel. While U.S. State Secretary Antony Blinken acknowledged the historical ties between Hamas and Iran, he stated that there's no direct evidence pointing to Iran's orchestration of the current attack. Egypt's Foreign Ministry has also sounded alarms about the situation's escalation and called for restraint from both Israel and the Palestinians. The U.S. State and Defense Departments have yet to make official comments on McCaffrey's statements or the evolving situation in the region.

It seems to me that most people don't really understand what the fuss in Israel is all about, particularly as Jews have their own, capable, strong country, and Palestinians are - as media often report - living in dire poverty behind guarded, concrete barriers. It's very easy to start thinking that those poor people deserve some sort of statehood of their own and that Jews are their oppressors. It's also easy to be deceived into believing that the entire conflict has been going on for so long and is so complicated that surely, at the very least, both sides are to blame. üî¥ The reality is far simpler and I've decided to sum it up in three points in the image attached. Only one side of this conflict has ever accepted to live side-by-side with the other, in two separate countries. Only one side agreed to share the holy city of Jerusalem, important to Jews, Christians and Muslims alike, under independent, international jurisdiction. The Jewish side. And while it seems that Israel is a powerful nation, it's only inhabited by 9 million people, 2 million of whom are Arabs with Israeli passports. That leaves 7 million Jews surrounded by 460+ million Arabs living in neighbouring countries in the Middle East and North Africa + 88 million Iranians. These proportions have always been skewed heavily against the Jews, so they never wanted to start any wars. They just wanted to finally have a small country of their own, in their historical homeland that they had migrated to since the 19th century, following hundreds of years of deprivation and the Holocaust in which 6 million had been methodically exterminated by the Nazis. That's all. To frame these people as some sort of bloodthirsty occupiers is an absurdity of monumental proportions. However, these weaknesses also explain why Arabs were never interested in any talks or compromise - they were just so convinced of their numerical superiority that they did not think it possible that any Jewish state could survive. Today we're often hearing about Jewish settlers dividing the West Bank into smaller and smaller pockets that Palestinians can live in but the fact of the matter is that Jews never wanted the West Bank, which was under Jordanian control until 1967. They captured the area during the Six Day War, after pleading with Jordanian king not to take part in the conflict but he refused. In the very same war they captured Sinai, which they later returned to Egypt in exchange for recognition and peace. For the longest time West Bank was considered just another bargaining chip and the settlement policy started as a security measure, given the persistent Arab threat. And yes, after decades of indiscriminate terrorism and failed promises by Palestinian leaders, it has become a de facto policy of squeezing Palestinians out. But it was not intended in the first place - Jews were more than content with the original 1947 plan and just wanted space for themselves, away from bombs, bullets and gas chambers. That's all. So, fast-forward several decades, what you're seeing today is not Israel oppressing poor Palestinians but rather a victim that has overpowered his oppressor, containing him to isolated, controlled areas, limiting the harm that he can inflict. And if you take pity on Palestinians today you have to remember that the conditions they live in are a consequence of seven decades of trying to get rid of Jews. And even now they voted Hamas into power in 2006 and the organisation's leader, Ismail Haniyeh, would still win their presidential election today (if they ever got round to calling one). Choices have consequences.

#Nkgono_Mantsopa

Powerful women of Africa II
Mantsopa Makhetha

Prophetess Anna Mantsopa Makhetha was born in 1795 at a place called Likotsi or Ramakhetheng near present day Maseru. She is the daughter of Nkopane, elder brother of Makhetha, and Sesilane. The name she was given at birth is Koena-li-fule, which means ‚Äúthe crocodiles are feeding/ crocodile feed‚Äù.  When she was young she witnessed the horrors of famine caused by the Difaqane, which forced many people to turn to cannibalism and sadly this is how she lost her father.

She was also taken captive for 6 months by an Nguni group called Amankowane (or Mankoane), who swept down the country in pursuit of Pakalitha and his AmaHlubi. Fortunately, she managed to escape when some of her relatives came into the area trading animal skins for mealies. 

Mantsopa was supposed to marry her cousin Lekote (son of her father‚Äôs elder brother, Makhetha), but he died shortly after the dowry cattle were handed over. She, therefore, got married to his brother, Selatile, who already had five wives and bore four children (three daughters and one son namely; Ntsopa, Motsielehi, Ts‚Äôiu and Sesilane).

As is customary in the Basotho culture for a mother to change her name after the birth of her first child by adding the prefix ‚ÄúMa or Mma‚Äù to the name of the first child, she became MaNtsopa. It is believed that she inherited her healing, rainmaking, divining and prophesying powers from her uncle Mohlomi, who had trained a young and ambitious Moshoeshoe before becoming his political advisor.

During the early 1850s Mantsopa prophesied that the Basotho would win a battle against the British troops led by Major Warden. She became renowned as a prophetess, living legend and advisor to Moshoeshoe I when her prophesies about successive wars were fulfilled. Eugene Casalis (French missionary) recalled how, in anticipation of conflict with Major Warden's forces in 1851, Moshoeshoe was only concerned about whether to await the enemy or to commence the attack thanks to Mantsopa.

Over time she prophesised many victories including that over Batlokwa of Sekonyela in 1853 and predicted many events such as the rinderpest epidemic that followed World War I.  However, her role as an advisor to Moshoeshoe ended in 1868 when the British annexed Basutoland (Lesotho). That same year, she was baptised by a French missionary called Theophile Jousse and given the name Anna.

Soon after, she moved to Modderpoort (outside Ladybrand in the Free State) and joined Anglican missionaries. Although she had been baptised as a Christian, Mantsopa continued working with herbs and divining. This did not sit well with the missionaries as they regarded what she did as black magic, but she still continued.

Her conversion to Christianity was in itself surprising, because her early encounters with the missionaries were ambivalent. They disagreed on a lot of things such as how she did not believe that she needed the bible to reach God as she already had direct contact with him through her visions.  She also disputed the missionary contention that the road to reach God was narrow, saying that the path in her view was wide to accommodate many people. Nonetheless, she agreed that there was one God, but remained critical of what she perceived as an anti-Basotho notion in their teachings. 

She died at the age of 111 and was buried with Christian rites in the Modderpoort cemetery, alongside the Brothers of the Society of St Augustine and the white residents of Modderpoort. Her grave, the cave where she prayed and the freshwater spring (reputedly pointed out to Mantsopa as a source of ‚Äòsacred‚Äô water by her ancestor) are major tourist attractions visited mostly by pilgrims who go there for various reasons (e.g. for prayers, to collect water from the sacred spring or to pay respects to the memory of their prophetess).  The Free State Provincial Heritage Resources Authority declared the grave and cave as provincial heritage sites.

Hamas launched a large-scale attack against Israel from the Gaza Strip on Saturday, October 7, a day after the 50th anniversary of the start of the Yom Kippur War, also known as the 1973 Arab-Israeli War.‚Å†
‚Å†
On October 6, 1973, Egypt and Syria launched a surprise attack on Israeli positions in the Sinai Peninsula and Golan Heights. Magnum photographers @michabaram.archive, @leonardfreed, @abbas.photos and Bruno Barbey closely documented the ensuing 19-day armed conflict between Israel and a coalition of Arab states led by Egypt and Syria.‚Å†
‚Å†
Hamas began this weekend‚Äôs attack with a barrage of rockets while militants crossed the border into Israel, killing and taking civilians and soldiers hostage. Israel has since formally declared war, responding with heavy airstrikes and cutting off electricity in Gaza. Both sides have suffered hundreds of casualties.‚Å†
‚Å†

Israel currently provides food, fuel and electricity to palestinians in Gaza. The Israeli government says it will cut off these provisions, to Palestinians who are already suffering and displaced. They will turn to other neighbors, including Egypt, to fill the vacuum. 

Israel is seeking ways to retaliate that won‚Äôt threaten the lives of the hostages in Gaza, so perhaps this is one motive for this choice. It is also true that some members of the Israeli government have said terrible dehumanizing things about the Palestinian civilian population; the government is made up of many far-right extremists unpopular with the majority of the Israeli public. There have been mass protests in the streets for months because so many Israelis object to the extremists and their policies. 

Hamas is an Iran-backed terrorist organization that drove out the governing leadership of the Palestinian Authority in 2007 and has controlled Gaza ever since. Hamas has conducted suicide attacks against civilians and kidnappings. Hamas does not recognize Israel‚Äôs right to exist and supports the extermination of Jews and the creation of fundamentalist state throughout the region. There are other Palestinian leaders who have worked for peace and co-existence. Hamas is not that. 

If you want to offer more context or a different way to frame these developments please do so with compassion and curiosity. Righteousness, intolerance, cruelty are not welcome here.

Israel has declared a ‚Äúcomplete siege‚Äù of Gaza, cutting off water, food and power supplies, as Hamas militants threatened to start killing Israeli civilian hostages if the bombing of civilian areas in the enclave continued without prior warning.

Palestinian militants abducted more than 100 people during a surprise multi-front attack in which they killed more than 700 ‚Äì making Saturday the deadliest day in Israel‚Äôs history. Israeli media said on Monday the death toll had climbed to 900, with 2,616 injured.

In response, Israel has pounded the Palestinian enclave of Gaza, killing hundreds of people in retaliation. The death toll in Gaza has risen to 560, with 2,900 injured, according to Palestinian authorities.

Israel‚Äôs Iron Dome missile shield is considered among the most advanced defence systems in the world.

It was specially designed to protect against a range of incoming short-range threats.

The Iron Dome uses radar to identify and destroy incoming threats before they can cause damage.

It can differentiate between missiles likely to hit built-up areas and those that won't. Static and mobile units only launch interceptor missiles to shoot down anything interpreted as dangerous.

The system became operational in 2011 and was developed by Israel with some US support.

Rockets used by Palestinian militant group Hamas often struggle to evade the Iron Dome system - but thousands were fired in a short space of time to overwhelm it on Saturday.

Baldwin IV, the 12th-century King of Jerusalem, faced a formidable adversary from a young age. Afflicted by leprosy, he ascended to the throne at the tender age of 13. Despite the physical toll of his ailment, Baldwin IV displayed exceptional courage and strategic brilliance. Known as the "Leprous King," he valiantly led his forces against the renowned Muslim general, Saladin.

Baldwin's reign was marked by intense conflict, including the famous Battle of Montgisard in 1177. Despite being outnumbered, the young king,  who was 16 at the time, devised a daring plan, surprising Saladin's forces and achieving a remarkable victory. His tenacity and leadership earned him respect even from his adversaries.

The challenges posed by leprosy, however, were relentless. As his health deteriorated, Baldwin struggled to maintain stability in the kingdom. Despite his condition, he demonstrated a commitment to his people, making significant efforts to secure the realm's future.

Baldwin IV's story is one of resilience, leadership, and sacrifice. Despite facing insurmountable odds, he left an indelible mark on history, remembered not only for his military triumphs but also for his unwavering dedication to his kingdom in the face of a debilitating illness.ü™∂

‚ÄúFor the first time in decades, Israel called the conflict with Palestinians a state of war.

But for Palestinians, being at war is an enduring reality that has shaped their daily lives for the past seven decades.

Since the Palestinian Nakba in 1948, which resulted in the forcible displacement of 750,000 Palestinians from their towns and villages, successive Israeli governments have committed hundreds of human rights violations, including ethnic cleansing, apartheid, and mass killings, all of which amount to war crimes according to international law.

While Palestinians have long said that Israel‚Äôs practices are part of a war waged against their very existence, Israel has managed to get away with its violations, enjoying complete impunity that has lasted for more than 75 years.

At 6.30am on Saturday, residents in Gaza were abruptly awakened by the sound of explosions reverberating through the blockaded Strip. By this time, it was not another Israeli military assault; rather, it was barrages of Palestinian homemade rockets launched towards several towns and cities in Israel.

While the attack is described as ‚Äòsurprising‚Äô by many, an escalation of events was undoubtedly expected, given Israel‚Äôs tightening of restrictions and the rise in assaults across the occupied Palestinian territories during the past few months.

This rise in Israeli military and settler brutality signifies an unprecedented level of violence across all the Palestinian territories, fueled and encouraged by a troubling sense of impunity and a lack of accountability for those responsible.

Residents of Gaza have been talking of a fresh escalation since the early months of 2023: those discussions became ever more prominent both during and following each Israeli surge in violence in the occupied territories.

And for them, the attack by Palestinian armed factions against Israel this weekend was not so much a surprise in concept as in scale and nature, both of which were unprecedented in the history of the Israeli-Palestinian conflict.‚Äù

I often talk about people-pleasing isn‚Äôt really about pleasing people; it‚Äôs how we learned to stay physically, emotionally, or socially safe. But this coping mechanism we learned in the past wreaks havoc on our relationships in the present. 

Ultimately, people-pleasing‚Äôs inevitable consequences‚Äîyears‚Äô worth of resentment, avoidance, conflict aversion, and unspoken grievances‚Äîinhibit us from truly connecting with the very people we care about. They also prevent others from knowing who we really are.

True intimacy requires that we release our stronghold on this outdated coping mechanism. It requires that we share the depths of our own passions and dreams. It demands that we are honest about what we feel and need, even when it‚Äôs hard. Ultimately, accepting the invitation to intimacy means bringing more self to our relationships after years of bringing less. 

THIS Thursday, October 12, join me at my new talk, Using Fierce Compassion to Stop People-Pleasing and Start Being Real, where we‚Äôll discover how we leverage our natural care and compassion for others as tools to break the people-pleasing pattern once and for all. Get your tickets today at the link in my bio. (Can‚Äôt make it live? A ticket gets you access to the recording afterwards!)

Misunderstanding is a complex and sometimes hurtful emotion that we all experience at some point in our lives. It's that feeling when someone interprets our words or actions in a way we never intended, leading to confusion and sometimes even conflict.

Sending a message that was misread, saying something innocently that was taken the wrong way, or trying to explain our viewpoint but being met with resistance instead of understanding. It's like a knot in our chest, tightening with every passing moment, making us question our ability to convey our intentions. 

It's essential to remember that communication is a two-way street. It's easy to feel hurt or defensive but taking a step back and approaching the situation with empathy can lead to a resolution.

It's crucial to have open and honest conversations, allowing space for clarifications and explanations. 

Understanding that it's natural for misunderstandings to occur, and we all have our own perspectives. Instead of pointing fingers, let's strive to listen actively, seek to understand, and extend the benefit of doubt.

Remember, words have power, but misinterpretations can arise irrespective of our intentions. A warm smile can go a long way in bridging the gap caused by misunderstandings. 

Let's make an effort to be patient, loving, and compassionate towards one another, acknowledging that we are all unique individuals trying to navigate this complex world.

Next time you find yourself caught in a web of misunderstanding, take a deep breath, and remind yourself that clarity can be achieved if both parties are willing to communicate with an open heart and an open mind. A lot of new people have started following me in regard to the current events in Israel. I would like to introduce myself to those who have not heard of me before: I AM NOT AN ACTIVIST. 

I am first and foremost a novelist. A writer. A journalist. I don't want to educate. I want to sit in my bed and invent protagonists and weird stories and read books and listen to music and dream. I was born and raised in Berlin, East-Berlin, when there was still a different state and a wall. My father is Jewish and I have cleared my halachical status through a German Beit Din. Therefore I am Jewish and member of the Jewish Community in Germany. In 1991 I traveled to Israel the very first time to meet my family and flew back over and over again. So I know this country for 32 years. Since ten years I am living between Berlin and Tel Aviv. I have an 8 years old German-Israeli daughter. 

In 2015 my first novel was published by @sfischerverlage called "Wintern√§he" in which I write about the Israeli-Arab-conflict, Jewish identity and antisemitism. If you'd read it now, you had the feeling it was written yesterday. Which is odd even to me. For years I have been writing for basically all German newspapers and magazines covering topics like feminism, Jewish life in Germany, financial freedom and sex. So basically I write about sex, money and Jews. My bones are filled with humor, my heart with optimism, my brain with curiosity. I studied Philosophy and History at Humboldt University. Former ad^It star Mia Khalifa expresses solidarity with Palestine amidst escalating Israel-Palestine conflict.

#war #israel #palestine #miakhalifa #explorepage‚ú®

There are a lot of people online talking about the Israel-Palestine conflict right now. People are picking sides (because that's what we do). Israeli forces have ramped up attacks following an attack from Hamas. Netanyahu is promising that his response will change the future of the occupation and conflict. But, Palestinian resistance forces and Hamas have never had the military power or global support Israel has. Nor have the Palestinian people currently living on occupied lands on the Gaza Strip ever really had freedom of movement and safety (or nationhood) they deserve. We are watching genocide happen.

People are using ideological shortcuts to determine when violence is justified, necessary, or warranted.

Rather than enter a political debate that predates me and that I have not, myself, participated in organizing around, I would rather just focus on the ways that we condone violence and genocide when powerful people, institutions, and nations suggest its the only way forward. 

We hold space for violence when it's enacted by countries with asymmetric military power, nuclear arms, and political cache among other developed nations. We are fine with violence when it preserves the status quo and keeps our existing political relationships intact.

It's only when marginalized and oppressed people defend themselves that we see calls to end the violence. Protestors are cast as aggressors when their goal is merely survival. 

This is the colonial project at work. Notice it. Call it out. There are people who cannot speak in this moment. 

This is not about our political beliefs and sides. It's about the belief that human beings deserve to live and live fully.

Tweet grabs: Whenever Black and Brown people resist oppression, we are cast as violent, aggressive, and riotous. But, the oppressors are silent about the violence they've enacted, typically for generations.

This is how colonization works. Rewriting history is central to this process.

When you chastise oppressed people for resisting because "it will make things harder for them," you're siding with the oppressors.

#Netanyahu said his country was now at ‚Äúwar‚Äô‚Äô with #Hamas, which is considered a terrorist organization by #Israel and the US. Though understandable, or even inevitable, given the moment, this wasn‚Äôt a good sign. Wars demand clear battlefield victories that don‚Äôt necessarily bring strategic ones, and Israel‚Äôs strategic priority right now should be containment. This conflict could grow a lot worse if allowed.

The more substantive part of Netanyahu‚Äôs statement on Saturday was hard to fault. He divided his prescription for the days and weeks ahead into three parts: First, clear Hamas fighters from Israeli territory and restore security to the border; second, exact a price from Hamas, including in #Gaza, while securing other borders to ensure nobody else attacks; and finally, unite and remain level-headed. It's the second and third parts that will be hard to stick to, so let‚Äôs take them one at a time.

One of the most common situations which may happen to any thinker is undoubtedly doubting his own principles and opinions that often have to be met with the pressure of opposing ideas. According to Friedrich Nietzsche, tired people are more susceptible to ideas, which were defeated by them some time ago, because during this period man exposes himself to an apparently positive influence which, in fact, should never be allowed to speak again seriously for the reason of giving people pure illusions without any piece of truth from reality. Nonetheless, a great deal of people consider this state to be extremely useful and crucial to our development, as it undermines our current views, forcing us to intelligently defend our most important claims. Although in theory we fight the same views, constantly, new counter-arguments along with dilemmas appear in our consciousness, concluding with the direct conflict of our values with foreign concepts. So does the feeling of fatigue, bringing old ideas down on us, directly harm people? Or maybe it is a test that is an ideal opportunity for future¬† development?
_
Generally speaking, I would be more likely to agree with the second group about the properties of the event as a whole. By returning old ideas in a new form, man is able to show his willpower in the face of an overnight threat, which practically never forgives us, while always pushing our interior until one side finally wins. Of course, one possible scenario is that the person will be¬† possessed by persuasive and sinister views, but in most cases the risk is worth the potential gains. Therefore, despite the numerous dangers to which fatigue exposes us, including prevalent illusions such as popular truisms, a man should definitely oppose the slightest sign of them in order to crystallize his own courage and strengthen the power of his arguments or abandon his current principles for the sake of more meaningful statements.

After the start of this most recent war in Israel, I‚Äôve seen people make some wild and uneducated assumptions on where weapons used by Palestinian armed groups come from.

The majority of the fighting happening in early October in 2023 in Israel / Palestine is happening around Gaza. 

There are a fewer number of AR15 pattern assault rifles in the hands of armed groups in Gaza than there are in Groups based in ‚Äúrefugee camps‚Äù in the West Bank. This is because Gaza has a ocean border and land border with Egypt, meaning other arms besides IDF ‚ÄúM4‚Äôs‚Äù are easier to acquire via smuggling than they are in the more heavily Israeli controlled West Bank.

A majority of AR15s used by armed Palestinian groups actually came from Israel via theft, corruption, or capture during a conflict. The few AR15s that are not from the IDF are usually older M16A1 or M16A2 pattern rifles or carbines that are smuggled into Gaza.

Most of these AR15s in the hands of armed Palestinian groups do vaguely resemble ‚ÄúM4‚Äôs‚Äù, but are in fact mainly M16A1 rifles that have been converted into carbines by the IDF. Some of these are modified further by Palestinians such as the rifle in slide 4 which has had its fixed carry handle removed. Companies like DS Arms in the United States provided the Israelis with ‚Äúupgrade kits‚Äù to turn M16A1 assault rifles & other older carbines into more modern ‚Äúflat top‚Äù AR15 carbines.

Some AR15s used by Palestinian groups are actually not AR15s, but just look the part from a distance. Slide 5 & 6 show a 9x19mm carbine that is designed to vaguely look like an AR15.

In reality, the AR15 is not the primary rifle of armed groups in Gaza, as the AK is way more prolific in the area.

Jordan‚Äôs King Abdullah spoke to regional and international leaders on Sunday in a bid to de-escalate the rising tensions between Israel and the Palestinians.

In a telephone conversation with Egypt‚Äôs President Abdel Fattah El-Sisi, the king warned of the repercussions a prolonged conflict could have on regional security, the Jordan News Agency reported.

The leaders agreed on the need for both Palestinians and Israelis to demonstrate self-restraint, protect civilian lives and adhere to international humanitarian law, while also reiterating their support for the Palestinian cause.

In a conversation with Iraqi Prime Minister Mohammed Shia Al-Sudani, King Abdullah said coordination among Arab nations was vital in supporting the Palestinians to achieve their legitimate rights.

He also reiterated the need for collective action to prevent the conflict from escalating.

The king also spoke to European Council President Charles Michel about the situation. He stressed the need to find a just solution to the Palestinian-Israeli conflict and said cooperation between Jordan and the EU was vital to achieving peace in the region.

Earlier today, Max Voloshin went out to purchase groceries for displaced families from southern communities in Israel. (Max is one of our employees and our building manager in Jerusalem.) We also donated groceries to an organization that distributes food to the IDF soldiers who are currently amassed on Israel‚Äôs borders in preparation for the conflict over the coming days and weeks. We have opened up our home, and the Glory of Zion Jerusalem Ministry Center to accommodate families from the south who need to take shelter outside of the Gaza area. We are so blessed to have the Ministry Center and home in Jerusalem to serve the community in this way.

Today, we give flowers to @rigobertamenchu ‚Äî Mayan k‚Äôiche‚Äô human rights activist, feminist, and Nobel Peace Prize laureate

Born in 1959 in Chimel, a small Mayan community in Guatemala, Rigoberta traveled to communities teaching rural campesinos their rights. 

During ethnic and socioeconomic tensions and war, Rigoberta and her family mobilized Guatemalans to denounce government-led mass atrocities.

Rigoberta and her family‚Äôs activism led to their targeting as her father and other campesinos were murdered in a fire and her brother and mother were tortured years later. 

By the time, the peace agreement was signed, ending the 42-year-long conflict, 450 Mayan villages were destroyed, more than 200,000 Guatemalans were murdered and 1 million were displaced. 

Rigoberta fled to Mexico in 1981 and continued her work for the rights of indigenous peoples. 

In her book, ‚ÄúI, Rigoberta Mench√∫‚Äù she continued to share her story and later helped to define and distinguish the concept of ‚Äúindigenous peoples.‚Äù 

Later, in 1992, Rigoberta was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize for her ‚Äústruggle for social justice and ethno-cultural reconciliation based on respect for the rights of indigenous peoples.‚Äù

In 2006, Rigoberta and five other Nobel laureates established the Nobel Women's Initiative to promote peace, justice and equality for women.

Today, Rigoberta continues her work promoting the rights of indigenous people, women, equality, and peace.

‚úäüèΩThe Rigoberta Mench√∫ Tum Foundation (FRMT) plays a vital role in supporting Mayan governments and seeking justice through advocating in several high-profile cases. 

‚úäüèΩIn 2013, Rigoberta was appointed as a Special Investigator within the Autonomous National University of Mexico (UNAM) Multicultural Nation Program to investigate and seek justice for all Mayan people impacted by the genocide.

Today, we give Rigoberta flowers for her dedication to ensuring justice for indigenous peoples and her perseverance despite facing numerous systemic and oppressive obstacles.

An adverse economic impact of the conflict is expected worldwide. India, too, is not excluded from the spillover effects.

IMPACT ON INDIA-ISRAEL BILATERAL TRADE
According to the Embassy of India in Israel, the trade (excluding defence) between the two countries stood at USD 10.1 billion in the financial year 2022-23. That fiscal, Indian merchandise exports to Israel were valued at $7.89 billion and Israeli exports to India were $2.13 billion.

India's major exports to Israel include automotive diesel, chemical and mineral products, machinery and electrical equipment, plastics, textile and apparel, transport equipment, and agricultural products. India primarily imports defence machinery, petroleum oils, electrical equipment and transport equipment.

The bilateral trade could take a hit if the Israel-Hamas war is prolonged, as Israel's resources would then get concentrated towards conflict response.

EFFECT ON OIL PRICES
Although Israel and Palestine are not major oil players, the violent conflict at the moment is happening in a broader key oil-producing region. Crude has already spiked as much as 5% intraday on fears that Israel-Hamas war may escalate even further.

US-brokered talks to normalize Saudi-Israel relations will likely be put on hold. This may delay oil production and reduce prices, a report by Mumbai-based risk consultancy firm Mitkat Advisory said.
