List of major wars and conflicts between Israel and Arab states:

1. 1948 Arab-Israeli War (First Arab-Israeli War): Fought immediately after the declaration of the State of Israel in 1948, involving Arab states including Egypt, Jordan, Syria, Lebanon, and Iraq.

2. Suez Crisis (1956): A conflict primarily involving Egypt, the United Kingdom, France, and Israel, triggered by Egypt's nationalization of the Suez Canal.

3. Six-Day War (1967): Israel fought against Egypt, Jordan, and Syria, resulting in Israel gaining control of the Sinai Peninsula, West Bank, and Golan Heights.

4. War of Attrition (1967-1970): A series of skirmishes and battles along the Suez Canal and the Israeli-Egyptian border.

5. Yom Kippur War (1973): Egypt and Syria launched a surprise attack on Israel during Yom Kippur, leading to a ceasefire.

6. Lebanon War (1982): Israel invaded Lebanon to remove the Palestinian Liberation Organization (PLO) from southern Lebanon, also involving Syrian forces.

7. First Intifada (1987-1993): A Palestinian uprising against Israeli rule in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.

8. Second Intifada (2000-2005): Another Palestinian uprising against Israeli occupation, marked by increased violence.

9. Lebanon War (2006): A conflict between Israel and Hezbollah, a Shiite militant group based in Lebanon.

10. Gaza-Israel Conflicts (Various): Ongoing conflicts between Israel and Palestinian groups in the Gaza Strip, including Hamas and Islamic Jihad, with notable events like Operation Cast Lead (2008-2009), Operation Pillar of Defense (2012), and Operation Protective Edge (2014).

The Israeli‚ÄìPalestinian conflict is an ongoing military and political conflict beginning in the mid-20th century, and the world is deeply concerned about the current escalation of tension and violence between Palestine and Israel.

When people discuss Israel and Palestine, it may be easy to think of hatred and conflict. Such a stereotype prompted the French artist JR to create the "Face2Face" project in 2007.

JR photographed the locals of the same profession in several cities in Israel and Palestine, including teachers, musicians, actors, hairdressers, and students. He captured their exaggerated expressions at close quarters and exhibited their large-scale images side by side in Jerusalem and Bethlehem.

This gripping narrative follows the interconnected lives of Neha, Jack, & Elena as they navigate a world teetering on the brink of catastrophe.

The novel's premise explores a chilling scenario: global conflict leading to nuclear devastation & an uninhabitable Earth. It vividly depicts the catastrophic power of these weapons, forcing readers to confront this terrifying possibility.

One of the central themes of the novel revolves around the responsibility of humanity in creating weapons of mass destruction. The narrative questions the wisdom of crafting instruments that could lead to our own annihilation. This ethical dilemma is skillfully woven into the storyline, prompting readers to reflect on the choices made by society & its leaders.

The characters of Neha, Jack, & Elena are compelling and relatable, providing a human face to the dire circumstances they find themselves in. Their individual journeys & experiences serve as a microcosm of the larger global crisis, allowing readers to empathize with the personal toll of war & its consequences.

What sets this book apart is its intriguing suggestion that salvation may come from beyond our world. The prospect of aliens from a different planet intervening to save Earth adds an element of mystery and wonder to the narrative. This imaginative twist challenges conventional thinking and introduces a glimmer of hope in an otherwise bleak scenario.

In conclusion, it is a riveting science fiction novel that not only entertains but also serves as a cautionary tale for our world community. It prompts readers to contemplate the destructive potential of our own creations & the urgent need for global cooperation & peace.

The IMF and World Bank gather in Morocco Monday for their first annual meetings on African soil in 50 years, under pressure to reform to better aid poor nations blighted by debt and climate change.

The International Monetary Fund and World Bank traditionally hold their annual gathering of finance ministers and central bank governors outside their Washington headquarters every three years.

The southern Moroccan city of Marrakesh was supposed to host it in 2021, but the gathering was postponed twice because of the Covid pandemic.

A powerful earthquake that killed nearly 3,000 people in the region south of Marrakesh last month threatened to derail the event again, but the government decided it could go ahead.

The IMF and World Bank last held their meetings in Africa in 1973, when Kenya hosted the event and some nations were still under colonial rule.

Half a century later, the continent faces an array of challenges ranging from conflict to a series of military coups to unrelenting poverty to natural disasters.

"A prosperous world economy in the 21st century requires a prosperous Africa," IMF Managing Director Kristalina Georgieva said in a speech in Abidjan last week.

Join us at Flowers, 21 Cork Street, London W1 during Frieze Week 10th-14th October for LOST GIRLS.

Thirty years on from our original collaboration with the charity War Child, we are delighted to host this fundraising exhibition, powerfully curated by the InFems Art Collective, with works donated by artists including Maggi Hambling, Ai Wei Wei, Caroline Coon, Nadia Duvall, Tewodros Hagos, Pam Hogg, Peter Howson, Linder, Tracey Moffatt, Penny Slinger and many more.  While boldly addressing the challenges faced by girls affected by war and coinciding with the UN's International Day of the Girl Child, LOST GIRLS aims to raise vital funds for War Child‚Äôs work.
 
This stunning painting by Hambling is one of the many pieces with all proceeds generously benefitting War Child, who are driven by a single goal ‚Äì ensuring a safe future for every child affected by war. It works in some of the hardest to reach places to support those who are hardest hit, aiming to reach children as quickly as possible when conflict breaks out and stay long after the cameras have gone to support them through their recovery.
 
Maggi Hambling‚Äôs ‚ÄòVictim XXXIX‚Äò is one of a series of portraits of unnamed casualties of war and war-torn landscapes. 

Learn more about it and purchase on Artsy via the link in our bio, view it and more in LOST GIRLS at 21 Cork Street during Frieze week 10th ‚Äì 14th October, 11am-6pm.

The manner in which a couple divides labor is often a major source of unhappiness in today‚Äôs marriage, which could translate to a higher risk of divorce. According to studies, women fundamentally take on a whole ‚Äúsecond shift‚Äù of work when they get home from their outside jobs. This can take a toll on the marriage. 

A recent Harvard interview with Eve Rodsky suggests that even when couples do divide more obvious household responsibilities like cooking and cleaning, women still do the primary heavy lifting for the ‚Äúemotional work‚Äù of tending to the home and children. 

When one spouse continues to take on a disproportionate share of the household responsibilities, it often results in the following:

- The affected spouse feels resentful and taken advantage of
- They feel more marital dissatisfaction
- They feel overburdened and depressed
- Risk of divorce increases

So... What is a fair division of labor? What isn‚Äôt fair?

To determine this, you might need to take a hard look at each person‚Äôs beliefs about gender roles. When spouses have differing beliefs about gender roles and household responsibilities, it can result in confusion and conflict. 

Many individuals grew up in households where the division of labor was gender-defined, fair or not. And although a person might intellectually understand the unfairness of this, they might also unwittingly slip into the well-worn grooves of the household they grew up in.

When spouses have differing ‚Äúgrooves‚Äù and beliefs about these roles, it can have a profound effect on the quality of their marriage. In fact, even when spouses do agree about what is and isn‚Äôt fair, an open and honest conversation is warranted.

Life is hard. 
There's war in far away lands. 
There's war in homelands. 
There's war in people's hearts. 
There's war in people's minds and bodies. 
There's accidents and suffering and seemingly no hope. 

But there is hope.
There is peace.
The scripture says it's not peace that the world can give,  but something better. 

The world's peace would be ease and freedom from any conflict. 
But Christ's peace is stronger,  better. 

Rather than taking us out of the conflict, He brings Himself into it.  He doesn't remove the hard, He increases our capability, our strength, our peace in the hard. 

Why!? Why would He not just save us from all the hurt!? That's a really great question that I don't know the answer to. 

But I believe, I hope, that that's not the point of this life.  It's not to just skate through life on cloud 9. It's to learn how to really love other people and to love and choose God. 

So maybe you're like me,  and you have a list of people who are really struggling,  and you hear other people's stories, and it's all too much.

If all you are feeling is darkness right now,  look for the light. There is light everywhere.  Turn to Christ,  He will gladly bring the light to your darkness. 

Christ is my light, my peace, my strength, and my Savior. 

And if Christ doesn't resegnate with you, look inward,  find your own light,  because you have in it you.  And then share it, WE can be the ones to bring light to the dark, to the overwhelm, and to the hopeless.

There were dozens of sovereign indigenous nations that once called the region in and around Charleston, home. When English colonists came to this land, it was chiefly occupied by the Kiawah. The Sewee, Yemassee, Kusso, and Edisto people were among others in the area, but it was mainly the Kiawah who were driven from their homes and confined on a reservation of sorts; a location today still named Kiawah Island. Throughout the history of interaction between southeastern Native nations and British colonists, there has been both cooperation and conflict. Historic Charleston Foundation acknowledges the original people who called this land home, and we honor their descendants who are still here. Happy Indigenous Peoples' Day!

To learn more about The First People of the South Carolina Lowcountry, we recommend Episode 220 of Nic Butler's podcast, The Charleston Time Machine. Images: Sunset over Kiawah Island, supplementary images from CCPL.

Hamas, or the Islamic Resistance Movement, is a prominent Palestinian militant group based in the Gaza Strip, a densely populated enclave housing over 2.1 million people. Founded in 1987 as an offshoot of the Muslim Brotherhood during the first Palestinian intifada, Hamas emerged as a defiant adversary of Israel. Sheikh Ahmed Yassin, a Palestinian cleric, was its founding figure, and it established its military wing, the Izzedine al-Qassam Brigades, around 1991. One distinguishing aspect of Hamas is its refusal to acknowledge the existence of Israel and its unwavering commitment to replacing Israel through armed struggle. The group seeks to establish a Palestinian state that spans from the Mediterranean Sea to the Jordan River. Given this stance, the United States designated Hamas as a terrorist organization in October 1997. Over the years, Hamas has employed various tactics, including the use of explosives, rockets, suicide bombings, and kidnappings, to target Israel. It has also received support from Iran, which has contributed to its military capabilities. Hamas's political influence has grown significantly in the Palestinian territories. It achieved a notable victory in the 2006 legislative elections in Gaza, defeating Fatah, the primary Palestinian political party that controls the West Bank. Israel has responded to Hamas's actions with military operations and a blockade that restricts imports and the movement of civilians, a strategy often described as collective punishment. This blockade and repeated Israeli strikes have had severe humanitarian consequences for Gaza, contributing to poor living conditions and infrastructure. Sometimes running has to take a backseat, and I‚Äôm actually quite comfortable with this. 
You may have noticed, I haven‚Äôt had much to say about my running as of late. For various reasons, it has had to be put on the back burner. Don‚Äôt get me wrong, I‚Äôve missed it, it‚Äôs a big part of my life and my health, both mentally and physically but with work being, to put it politely, hectic, and other areas of my life mounting up I‚Äôve had to prioritise. I am slowly building back up and feeling a little more hopeful that my health is on the up.
I‚Äôm also aware that sometimes you need to stop, take stock, in order  to actually move forward. It‚Äôs something I discuss with many clients.

True strength occurs when you know you have to deal with the potential inner critic for not being able to do what you feel like you should be able to do.
Too many people will put themselves in a position which is actually detrimental to their health- pushing their bodies, exercising when they are in pain, or not fuelling appropriately rather than deal with the potential voice and feelings that come after, when you actually take the time to do what your body needs in that moment. Call it FOMO, some people will call it resilience but true resilience is when you face up to your fears and sit with the difficult feelings and narrative that somehow you are falling short. 
Clients I work with talk about ‚Äúthe guilt‚Äù they know they will feel if they don‚Äôt complete the distance or if they eat the so-called ‚Äúforbidden‚Äù food. 
But is it guilt? Or is it fear of having to deal with ‚Äúthat voice?‚Äù
In all honesty,  if you  keep running those ultras, is that strength or just avoidance? 
True progress and recovery comes from taking responsibility. Accepting that inner conflict, turning up for yourself with compassion not judgement. 

Always remember that thoughts are not facts. They may be real, but you have the power over them. You don‚Äôt need to believe them. Instead ask yourself what is the evidence that these beliefs are true?

Oil prices rallied while the dollar and yen advanced Monday after Hamas launched a shock attack on Israel at the weekend, sparking fresh concerns about tensions in the Middle East.

The crisis fanned concerns about supplies of crude from the region at a time when supply worries are already high owing to Saudi Arabia and Russia‚Äôs output cuts.

It has also renewed fears about the impact on inflation, with energy costs a key driver of spiking prices, giving a fresh headache to central banks as they try to ease up on interest rate hikes to avoid recessions.

The surprise attack and Israel‚Äôs declaration of war in response to it have left more than 1,000 dead and raised concerns that a potential broadening of the conflict could draw in the United States and Iran.

‚ÄúKey for markets is whether the conflict remains contained or spreads to involve other regions, particularly Saudi Arabia,‚Äù said ANZ Group‚Äôs Brian Martin and Daniel Hynes.

‚ÄúInitially at least, it seems markets will assume the situation will remain limited in scope, duration, and oil-price consequences. But higher volatility can be expected.‚Äù

Both main contracts surged more than five percent in early Asian business before easing back as the day wore on.

However, SPI Asset Management‚Äôs Stephen Innes warned: ‚ÄúHistorical analysis suggests that oil prices tend to experience sustained gains after the Middle East crises.

‚ÄúMeanwhile, stocks tend to eventually recover and trend higher after an initial period of volatility. Safe-haven assets like gold and Treasurys, which initially see gains during such crises, tend to fade from their initial price spikes as the situation stabilises.

‚ÄúBut with Middle East analysts considering this to be a pivotal moment for Israel, the view looks incendiary in any current scenario.‚Äù

A decidedly risk-off mood also saw investors push into the safety of the dollar, which was up against the pound and euro, as well as the Australian and New Zealand dollars.

The yen, considered one of the safest currencies, strengthened against the greenback, though it still remains locked around 11-month lows.

Gold, another key haven, gained around one percent.

Israel relentlessly pounded the Gaza Strip early Monday as fighting raged with Hamas around the Gaza Strip and the death toll from the war against the Palestinian militants surged above 1,100.

The Israeli army said it hit more than 500 targets in the blockaded and impoverished Gaza Strip in overnight clashes, while fighting persisted in seven to eight locations inside Israel around the enclave.

It came two days after Hamas launched a barrage of rockets and sent a wave of fighters who gunned down civilians and took at least 100 hostages in a massive attack that took Israel by surprise.

Sunday, the government officially declared war on the Palestinian militant group that controls Gaza and Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has warned Israel to prepare for a ‚Äúlong and difficult‚Äù conflict.

More than 700 Israelis have been killed since Hamas launched its large-scale attack, the Israel Defence Forces (IDF) said on Monday. Another 1,200 people have been wounded, many critically.

In retaliation, Israeli air strikes have hammered the impoverished and blockaded Gaza Strip, an enclave of 2.3 million people, with officials there reporting at least 413 Palestinian deaths.

‚ÄúOvernight IDF fighter jets, helicopters, aircraft and artillery struck over 500 Hamas and Islamic Jihad terrorist targets in the Gaza Strip,‚Äù the military said in a statement.

‚ÄúWe‚Äôre still fighting. There are between seven to eight open places around Gaza (where) we have still warriors fighting terrorists,‚Äù military spokesman Richard Hecht told reporters.

‚ÄúWe thought by yesterday (Sunday) we would have full control. I hope we will by the end of the day,‚Äù he added.

Thick plumes of smoke billowed from the Palestinian enclave as the strikes continued in the early hours of the morning, an AFP correspondent reported.

Army spokesman Lieutenant Colonel Jonathan Conricus estimated around 1,000 Palestinian militants had participated in Hamas‚Äôs assault on Saturday, which he called ‚Äúby far the worst day in Israeli history‚Äù.

‚ÄúNever before have so many Israelis been killed by one single thing, let alone enemy activity in one day,‚Äù he said.

He likened it to ‚Äúa 9/11 and a Pearl Harbour wrapped into one‚Äù.

Foreign nationals are among those killed or kidnapped as fresh conflict broke out between Hamas and Israel over the weekend. The German Foreign Ministry said German nationals are among those abducted by Hamas, all of them dual Israeli-German citizens. On Saturday, German national Shani Louk was seen in the car of  Hamas militants in videos shared on social media. She had been attending a peace festival near Gaza. US media reports suggest several Americans were among the dead and US nationals among those abducted by Hamas. France said one of its nationals was killed in Israel, while several others were missing. Britain said one of its nationals, serving in the Israeli army, was killed on the Gaza border on Saturday. A second UK national is reported to be missing. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said on Sunday two of his country's nationals had died in the attacks. Thai Prime Minister Srettha Thavisin tweeted Sunday he had received reports from the Thai ambassador in Tel Aviv "that two Thai people had died from the violence." A Cambodian national was also reported dead in Israel. Ten citizens of Nepal were among those killed in the Hamas assault on Israel, the Himalayan republic's embassy in Tel Aviv said in a statement Sunday, without giving more details. Nepal had earlier said at least 11 Nepali agricultural students were missing. They were studying near the Gaza border. Four others were injured in the attacks.
Source: DW

The broad rage of nationalities caught up in this attack will likely lead to a much higher level of support for Israel's retaliation which is almost certainly going to be extensive. While there have been reports of numerous pro-Palestine protests around the globe, several counter-protests have resulted in violent confrontations. It is almost certain that this renewed conflict will last for some time, and will cost many lives.

Wow. That is the word I uttered out loud immediately upon finishing the total masterpiece that is Monica. Actually it was more like wow, wow, wow, wowwwwwww. In Clowe's own words, Monica is the story of a woman's life, from cradle to grave. But it's so much more than that. I was lucky enough to catch his talk @cartooncrossroads earlier this month, a deeply enriching and inspiring experience. One thing that really stuck out to me was his discussion of memory. He described a sensation of having memories of memories, that at this stage of his life, they have become distorted further and further over time. He also mentioned that after his mother passed, he really didn't have much family left, so all of these memories exist only in his own mind, no longer having anyone to corroborate any of these experiences from early life. There are so many vastly different entry points for me in this spectacular tome. Feelings of loss, loneliness, deep introspection into one's own life, being an outsider, loving your family members while simultaneously enduring the heavy weight of shared conflict and difficult emotions. Much like Patience, Monica's color palette is utterly beautiful. I lived with my grandparents growing up and they never updated their house. The kitchen was acid yellow, the tv room was brown and orange and my bedroom had dazzling pop flower wallpaper in stunning dayglo pinks, yellows, greens and blues. That vintage 1960s palette is forever burned in my heart and dna. Clowe's particular use of color tugs at my own distorted memory and comforts me deeply. Seven years in the making, you can feel every line, panel, word and color choice have been deeply considered. The Treaty of Bucharest, signed on August 10, 1913, was a pivotal agreement that marked the conclusion of the Second Balkan War and the redistribution of territories in the Balkan Peninsula. This treaty had far-reaching implications for the region's political landscape, leading to significant changes in borders and national sovereignty. The primary outcome of the Treaty of Bucharest was the territorial realignment among the Balkan states. Bulgaria, which had initiated the Second Balkan War in pursuit of greater territorial gains, suffered substantial losses. It ceded most of its acquired territories to neighboring states. Serbia, Greece, and Romania were among the primary beneficiaries, each expanding their respective borders at Bulgaria's expense. Key provisions of the treaty included the awarding of additional territory to Greece, including southern Macedonia and the island of Crete, and the expansion of Serbian and Romanian territories in the north. Serbia gained the Kosovo region and extended into northern and central Macedonia. Albania was made an independent state under a German prince. Bulgaria, on the other hand, was left with a significantly reduced territory.
The Treaty of Bucharest not only reshaped the geopolitical landscape of the Balkans but also sowed the seeds for future conflicts and rivalries in the region. Bulgaria's sense of grievance over territorial losses would contribute to its alignment with the Central Powers during World War I. The treaty illustrated the challenges of post-conflict negotiations and the complexities of addressing competing national aspirations and territorial disputes. The Balkans remained a volatile and contested region in the years leading up to World War I, with many of the tensions and rivalries from the Balkan Wars persisting throughout the 20th century.

At the same time, Hamas exchanged strikes with Israel over the Gaza Strip.

There have been no widespread reports of involvement by the Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps in this weekend's conflict in Israel outside of helping to plan the attack by Hamas forces.

Marxism in international relations is a theory rooted in the ideas of Karl Marx and Friedrich Engels. It focuses on the role of economic factors, class struggle, and capitalism in shaping global politics. Marxists see international relations as an extension of domestic class conflicts, with states representing the interests of ruling classes. They emphasize the impact of imperialism, global capitalism, and economic inequality on the international system. Marxism also critiques liberal theories and highlights the potential for global revolution to overthrow capitalism. While criticized for oversimplification, Marxism offers a unique perspective on power dynamics and the influence of economic forces in international relations. Marxist and Neo-Marxist international relations theories are structuralist paradigms which reject the realist/liberal view of state conflict or cooperation; instead focusing on the economic and material aspects. Marxist approaches argue the position of historical materialism and make the assumption that the economic concerns transcend others; allowing for the elevation of class as the focus of study. Marxists view the international system as an integrated capitalist system in pursuit of capital accumulation.
The real-life examples of Marxism in international relations revolve around economic exploitation and inequality between developed and developing countries. They include the outsourcing of labor to low-wage countries, resource extraction in developing nations, unequal terms of global trade, and the burden of debt on less powerful nations. These examples illustrate how Marxist concepts of capitalism, imperialism, and class struggle can be used to analyze and criticize the dynamics of global economics and international relations.

Brent was up 3% to nearly $87 a barrel at just after 4AM Eastern Time, while West Texas Intermediate also jumped 3% to just over $85 a barrel. Both benchmarks had spiked as much as 5% at the start of the trading session, before paring back some of those gains.

Crude prices rose amid concerns that major producers, including Iran and Saudi Arabia, could become embroiled in the conflict, potentially causing supply disruptions. The Wall Street Journal reported Saturday that Iranian security officials had helped plan the raids on Israel, citing senior members of the militant groups Hamas and Hezbollah.

"How Saudi Arabia, Iran, and the US get drawn into this will be key," Deutsche Bank managing director Jim Reid said in a note. "Geopolitical risk doesn't tend to linger long in markets but there are many second-order impacts that could come through in the weeks, months and years ahead from this weekends' developments."

Meanwhile, US stocks looked set to trade lower, with Wall Street worried that higher oil prices could trigger a flare-up in inflation that would encourage the Federal Reserve to carry on hiking interest rates.

Samp;P 500 futures slipped 0.6% ahead of the opening bell, while Nasdaq 100 futures were down 0.7%. The Dow Jones Industrial Average was on pace to shed around 200 points, coming off the back of a rough week where it erased all its gains year-to-date.

"Despite the geopolitical risks rising in the Middle East over the weekend, US equity futures remain relatively muted in their reaction to these events," strategists at Denmark's Saxo Bank wrote in a research note.

"Risk sentiment has not accelerated to the downside in early trading hours. However, it is important to note that the risk picture is very complicated in the short-term depending on how Israel decides to respond," they added.

Israel's own benchmark TA-35 stock-market index had plunged 6.5% Sunday, for its biggest loss in over three years.

The attacks started early Saturday, when militants used paragliders and broke through security fences on Israel's border with Gaza, killing more than 700 people and taking hundreds of civilians and military personnel captive. 

US officials told NBC News the attacks were likely a bid to derail high-stakes negotiations, backed by the US, that were underway to normalize Israel's relations with Saudi Arabia. 

Saudi Arabia has historically refused to recognize Israel's legitimacy, and hostilities between the states date back to the 1948 Arab-Israeli war. 

But Saudi Arabia's ruler, Mohammed bin Salman, is keen to exploit the economic benefits of potentially normalizing ties with Israel, and there were hopes that other Arab states would follow suit. 

Iran, Hamas' main backer, has long opposed attempts to normalize relations between Israel and its regional neighbors. 

The Financial Times reported on Sunday that US officials were trying to establish if there was any involvement in the Israel attacks by Iran, with conflicting reports emerging over the weekend on whether Iran was involved. 

The success of Israeli-Saudi talks now appears to be remote, with the concessions Riyadh requested in how Israel treats Palestinians even less likely to be agreed on in the wake of the attack, and Israel's declaration of war on Hamas. 

Hamas itself has said the attacks were a response to Israeli settlers entering the al-Aqsa mosque in Jerusalem, the third holiest site in Islam and a long-standing flash point.

But a Hamas official also told Reuters that the operation had been years in the making, meaning the group is likely seeking to exploit Muslim grievance over recent events at the site and the wider diplomatic situation is the real motive for the attack. 

"The reality is that while Hamas has dressed up the attack as a response to Israeli incursions around the al-Aqsa mosque in Jerusalem, it chose to trigger this conflict ‚Äì at this time and in the way it did ‚Äì as a way to impose itself in that wider diplomacy," wrote The Guardian's Middle East correspondent Peter Beaumont.

The Battle of Ecnomus, fought in 256 BC during the First Punic War, was not only the largest naval battle of its time but also a clear indication of Rome's emerging naval prowess and its ambition to dominate the Mediterranean.

In 256 BC, the First Punic War had been ongoing for years, with the control of Sicily being a major bone of contention between Rome and Carthage. Sicily's strategic importance, owing to its fertile lands and economic resources, made it a highly sought-after prize for both powers, intensifying the conflict.

Ecnomus was strategically vital as it lay along the sea route connecting Rome and Carthage. Command over this region was pivotal for maritime supremacy and the ability to reinforce troops and resources in Sicily.

Under the leadership of the Roman consul Marcus Atilius Regulus, the Roman fleet faced off against the Carthaginian fleet, led by Adherbal and Hamilcar, near the shores of Ecnomus in Sicily. The scale of this naval clash was immense, with hundreds of ships from both sides, including warships and transport vessels, participating.

The Battle of Ecnomus did not yield a clear victor, and both sides suffered substantial losses. Nevertheless, it battle showcased Rome's resolve to challenge Carthage's naval dominance and marked a turning point in its naval history. It also laid the foundation for Rome's journey to maritime supremacy. Although the outcome was inconclusive, it bolstered Rome's confidence and played a pivotal role in its ultimate victory in the First Punic War.

In conclusion, the Battle of Ecnomus highlights Rome's determination and growing naval capabilities during the First Punic War. This pivotal engagement, while not producing a clear winner, significantly influenced ancient history and established Rome as a formidable force both on land and at sea.

Let us stand together, bound by our shared humanity, and work towards a world where such senseless violence is nothing but a distant memory.

Down To Earth speaks to author Avedis Hadjian about the humanitarian crisis in the Armenian enclave of Nagorno-Karabakh in the South Caucasus

The long-running conflict between Azerbaijan and the ethnic Armenian enclave of Nagorno-Karabakh in the South Caucasus region ended on September 20, 2023, with Azerbaijani forces overrunning the enclave after a 10-month-long blockade, followed by a massive aerial and artillery campaign.

The enclave, which had an Armenian majority and an Azeri minority is now mostly devoid of its Armenians, who have moved across the border to Armenia.

The conflict, which has claimed thousands of lives since its start at the time of the breakup of the erstwhile Soviet Union, has now led to a humanitarian crisis with refugees streaming into Armenia.

US to send military ships,aircraft closer to Israel as conflict continues.

The United States will send multiple military ships and aircraft closer to Israel as a show of support, Defense Secretary Lloyd Austin said, with Washington believing Hamas' deadly attacks may have been motivated to disrupt a potential normalizing of Israel-Saudi Arabia ties.

Hamas fighters rampaged through Israeli towns as the country suffered its bloodiest day in decades on Saturday. Israel battered Palestinians with air strikes in Gaza on Sunday, with hundreds reportedly killed on both sides.

The spiraling violence threatens to start a major new war in the Middle East.

At least three Americans were among those killed, CNN reported on Sunday, citing a U.S. memo.

Austin in a statement said he ordered the moving of the USS Gerald R. Ford Carrier Strike Group to the Eastern Mediterranean closer to Israel. The force includes the carrier, a guided missile cruiser and four guided missile destroyers.

Austin also said the United States had also taken steps to augment U.S. Air Force F-35, F-15, F-16, and A-10 fighter aircraft squadrons in the region. He said the United States would also provide munitions to Israel.

U.S. President Joe Biden told Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on Sunday that additional assistance for the Israeli Defense Forces was on its way to Israel and more would follow in the coming days, the White House said after their call. U.S. Vice President Kamala Harris also held a call with Israeli President Isaac Herzog.

The Pentagon in a later statement said Austin spoke to Israeli Defense Minister Yoav Gallant to update him on U.S. responses and "to express support for the people of Israel and to receive updates on Israel's operation to restore security and safety from Hamas' terrorist attack."

"The Secretary reaffirmed the unwavering support of the United States for Israel's right to defend itself," the statement said. It said Austin underscored that the U.S. steps "were taken to strengthen the U.S. military posture in the region to bolster regional deterrence efforts."

The recent conflict between Hamas and Israel threatens to disrupt negotiations between Saudi Arabia, Israel, and the U.S. aimed at establishing formal relations between Saudi Arabia and Israel. 

These talks involve Saudi recognition of Israel in exchange for U.S. weapons sales, security guarantees, and assistance in developing a civilian nuclear program. 

While Saudi Arabia has called for de-escalation and reiterated its support for a two-state solution to the Israeli-Palestinian conflict, the violence in Israel and Gaza complicates the prospects for these negotiations.

Prayer for Peace‚ÄîPope Francis

Lord God of peace, hear our prayer!

We have tried so many times and over so many years to resolve our conflicts by our own powers and by the force of our arms. How many moments of hostility and darkness have we experienced; how much blood has been shed; how many lives have been shattered; how many hopes have been buried‚Ä¶ But our efforts have been in vain.

Now, Lord, come to our aid! Grant us peace, teach us peace; guide our steps in the way of peace. Open our eyes and our hearts, and give us the courage to say: ‚ÄúNever again war!‚Äù; ‚ÄúWith war everything is lost‚Äù. Instill in our hearts the courage to take concrete steps to achieve peace.

Lord, God of Abraham, God of the Prophets, God of Love, you created us and you call us to live as brothers and sisters. Give us the strength daily to be instruments of peace; enable us to see everyone who crosses our path as our brother or sister. Make us sensitive to the plea of our citizens who entreat us to turn our weapons of war into implements of peace, our trepidation into confident trust, and our quarreling into forgiveness.

Keep alive within us the flame of hope, so that with patience and perseverance we may opt for dialogue and reconciliation. In this way may peace triumph at last, and may the words ‚Äúdivision‚Äù, ‚Äúhatred‚Äù and ‚Äúwar‚Äù be banished from the heart of every man and woman. Lord, defuse the violence of our tongues and our hands. Renew our hearts and minds, so that the word which always brings us together will be ‚Äúbrother‚Äù, and our way of life will always be that of: Shalom, Peace, Salaam!

Amen.
